@Node Introduction
@{u}So what does it do ?@{uu}

MUIRequestString is a tiny CLI command that pops up a string requester and
writes the user input to the standard output (stdout) of the process.
This is quite useful for interactive scripts in conjunction with the shell's
quoting mechanism.
@EndNode

@Node Features
· uses MUI, so it's GUI is freely configurable
· only 7.8 KBytes in size
· supports images in the body of the requester
· localized (German and English for now)
@EndNode

@Node Requirements
To run MUIRequestString you'll need:
· AmigaOS 3.0 (V39)
· MUI 3.8
· BetterString.mcc and BetterString.mcp 11.3
@EndNode

@Node Installation
1.copy BetterString.mcp and BetterString.mcc to MUI:Libs/mui or LIBS:mui.
2.copy MUIRequestString to C:
3.copy Catalogs/<yourlanguage>.catalog to LOCALE:Catalogs/<yourlanguage>
@EndNode

@Node Usage
Usage:

TITLE/A,BODY/A,ACCEPT/K,REJECT/K,MAXLEN/K/N

TITLE/A      is the title of the requester window. This argument must be
             provided. If the title includes spaces you need to enclose it with "".

BODY/A       is the body text of the requester window. This argument must be
             provided. If the body includes spaces you need to enclose it with "".
             You can include special formatting codes into the string, who will be
             interpreted as follows:

             *n                Starts a new line; so you can have multiline body text.
             ESC u             Switch on underlined text style.
             ESC b             Switch on bold text style.
             ESC i             Switch on italic text style.
             ESC n             Switches back to normal text style.
             ESC c             Switch on centered justification. Only valid at the
                               beginning of the string or after a newline.
             ESC l             Switch on left justification. Only valid at the
                               beginning of the string or after a newline.
             ESC r             Switch on right justification. Only valid at the
                               beginning of the string or after a newline (\\n).
             ESC I[5:filename] Include an image. You must provide the filename here.
                               If the filename contains spaces you must enclose it
                               with "" resp.*" *" (see below). AmigaOS' datatypes system
                               is used for loading
             ESC x             Set text color to pen x , where x is between 2 and 9.             
             ESC -             Switch off special character parsing. After that, e.g.
                               \\n will result in \\n and not in a new line.

             If you start MUIRequestString from the command line (from a shell,
             from an AmigaDOS batch file, or in DOpus as AmigaDOS command,...),
             ESC is represented by *e, a " within a string enclosed by "" is repre-
             sented by *". Look at the AmigaDOS documentation that should have been
             delivered with your copy of AmigaOS.


ACCEPT/K     is a string containing all characters the user is allowed to type into
             the string gadget. This argument is optional. Default is to allow any
             characters. If the ACCEPT string includes spaces you need to enclose it with "".

REJECT/K     is a string containing all characters the user is not allowed to type into
             the string gadget. This argument is optional. Default is to allow any
             characters. If the REJECT string includes spaces you need to enclose it with "".

             Note, that you can combine the latter two. So ACCEPT=" 123456" REJECT=4
             will allow for 1 2 3 5 6 and a blank.

MAXLEN/K/N   The maximum length of the string the user can type in. Default is 255
             characters.

?            Shows above template and asks you for input. If you provide a ? again, you
             will get a long description (/this) text.



Examples:

  MUIRequestString "This is the window title" "*ecHere you could place some info text*n or ask for input."

  This will ask the user for input. The body text of the requester is splitted into two lines (*n) and is
  centered. The input is printed to the console.


  setenv phone_number `MUIRequestString Request "*elPlease input your *ebphone number*en now!*n*eI[5:*"Work:My Picture File*"]" ACCEPT="1234567890" MAXLEN=20`

  Asks the user to input his phone number and saves it to a global environment variable called phone_number.
  The whole body is centered (*ec), the phrase "phone number" is displayed in bold text (*eb,*en).
  Line two displays the picture "My Picture File" in the "Work" volume. *" is necessary as a filename with
  white spaces in its name needs to be enclosed in quotation marks.
  The requester does not allow the input of characters other than 0 to 9.
  The phone number can not be longer than 20 characters.


@EndNode

@Node Rexx
MUIRequestString has an ARexx-Port.

Its name is MUIRequestString.x where x is the copy of MUIRequestString running.
So if you have it running three times at the same time it's MUIRequestString.1,MUIRequestString.2,...

It doesn't have any special rexx commands, only those every MUI application has. Have a
look at MUI's User Guide for more info on this.
@EndNode

@Node Bugs
No bugs known (so far...).
Tell me if you find one.
@EndNode

